title.children: Smith and Labuschagne take the fight to England on day one of Lord's Test

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: That is a terrific ball from Tongue! It has swung a mile in to Warner and his face betrayed that he knew he was beaten almost before the ball cannoned into the stumps. Warner goes for an at times fortunate 66 off 88 balls, punctuated with his normal attacking brilliance.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: BOWLED HIM! WARNER HAS TO GO!

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: That drizzle comes down a bit heavier and the players all go off. This is the sort of rain that is never really proper rain, but is definitely enough to disrupt and frustrate - sadly enough, all day.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Rain delay

children.content: That drizzle comes down a bit heavier and the players all go off.
This is the sort of rain that is never really proper rain, but is definitely enough to disrupt and frustrate - sadly enough, all day.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Well what a finish to the session, but England would definitely have wanted more after sending Australia in to bat under cloudy conditions on a greenish pitch. David Warner reached 50 at nearly a run a ball, and the English fielders had put down chances off both openers. Josh Tongue's late strike for his first Ashes wicket in just his second Test kept the session from being a total disaster for England and will make their lunch a much happier affair, but there's still a lot of work for England to do to justify Ben Stokes's decision to bowl first.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: LUNCH: Australia 1-73 (David Warner 53*)

props.alt: Stuart Broad shouts as David Warner sets off for a run.

children.content: Well what a finish to the session, but England would definitely have wanted more after sending Australia in to bat under cloudy conditions on a greenish pitch.
David Warner reached 50 at nearly a run a ball, and the English fielders had put down chances off both openers.

Josh Tongue's late strike for his first Ashes wicket in just his second Test kept the session from being a total disaster for England and will make their lunch a much happier affair, but there's still a lot of work for England to do to justify Ben Stokes's decision to bowl first.
